In that case, a couple of extensions of that which I use constantly:<p>cf&quot; is change find &quot;<p>But, since this is a grammar, there are other things than c we can use like d (delete find &quot;) or y (yank find &quot;). More than this we can swap out f. Instead of f, try i, which I think of as &quot;inside&quot;.<p>So ci&quot; deletes the text inside quotes and leaves you in insert mode. ci) deletes the text inside parentheses and leaves you in insert mode.<p>For example<p><pre><code>    foobar[somekeyvar] = &quot;wooyay&quot;

    move to somekeyvar and ci] then type &quot;anotherkey&quot;

    foobar[anotherkey] = &quot;wooyay&quot;
</code></pre>
I use this constantly while programming.
